#  Surface (verbatim from `src/main.rs` args_parse() function
#  using rust-argparse ArgumentParser):
#
#  Usage:
#    wasmedge_quickjs <file> [<arg>...]
#
#  Positional:
#    <file>                         JavaScript source file to
#                                   load and evaluate (typically
#                                   .js extension; the file is
#                                   read as UTF-8 text and
#                                   passed to QuickJS's
#                                   eval_buf with the file
#                                   path as the source-map
#                                   filename).  REQUIRED — the
#                                   parser exits with usage if
#                                   omitted.
#    <arg>...                       Arguments to pass to the
#                                   JavaScript program.  After
#                                   the file path is consumed,
#                                   remaining argv elements
#                                   become the "rest_arg" list
#                                   that's INJECTED as the
#                                   JavaScript `process.argv`
#                                   array (with the file path
#                                   inserted at index 0 to
#                                   match Node.js / Deno
#                                   conventions).  Empty by
#                                   default.
#
#  Auto-generated by rust-argparse:
#    -h, --help                     Show usage help and exit
#
#  Examples:
#    wasmedge_quickjs hello.js                     # Run hello.js (no args)
#    wasmedge_quickjs hello.js arg1 arg2           # Pass arg1/arg2 to JS via process.argv
#    wasmedge_quickjs ./server/main.js --port 8080 # Pass --port 8080 as user arg
#    wasmedge_quickjs --help                       # Show help
#
#  Notes:
#    - wasmedge_quickjs is INTENDED TO RUN INSIDE A WasmEdge
#      WebAssembly RUNTIME (typically invoked via `wasmedge
#      ./wasmedge_quickjs.wasm hello.js` rather than running
#      the native binary directly).  When compiled as a WASM
#      module and run via wasmedge, the resulting JS execution
#      is sandboxed in the WebAssembly security boundary —
#      no host filesystem/network access unless explicitly
#      granted via WASI capabilities.  This is the SERVERLESS-
#      EDGE deployment model used by Second State's
#      Cloudflare-Workers-like products.
#    - The native binary (this completion's target) is useful
#      for development / testing of JS scripts before deploying
#      them as WASM modules.
#    - Standard QuickJS extensions are available: Promises,
#      ES Modules (with import/export), async/await, top-level
#      await, Symbols, BigInt, WeakMap/WeakSet, etc.  See the
#      WasmEdge QuickJS API docs at https://www.secondstate.io/.
